solutions.content:
**Idea:** 2 pointers
* If array length is less than 3, there's nothing to do so exit
* Since the array is sorted, all duplicates will be consecutive. So use 2 pointers, one to point at the 3rd or higher occurence of a num, and another one to find the number that can replace the num at the first pointer
* Keep doing this until all 3+ repetitions of nums have been overwritten
* Example: `[0, 0, 1, 1, 1, 1, 2, 3, 3]`

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/ba998bdb-4241-469a-85e7-13f5ab60a97e_1644108233.2912471.png)
> **T/S:** O(n)/O(1), where n = size(nums)
```
public int removeDuplicates(int[] nums) {
	var i = 2;

	for (var j = i; j < nums.length; j++)
		if (nums[j] != nums[i - 2])
			nums[i++] = nums[j];

	return i;
}
```
Generic solution for when k repetitions are allowed
```
public int removeDuplicates(int[] nums, int k) {
	var n = nums.length;
	if (n < k + 1)
		return n;

	var i = k;
	for (var j = i; j < n; j++)
		if (nums[i - k] != nums[j])
			nums[i++] = nums[j];

	return i;
}
```
