# Intuition and Approach
Hey Folks👋🏼,
I am back with another **AMAZING** solution to a pretty complex problem (that you might think at this point) but let me give you a little spoiler😂 I will take the solution of an easy problem and add 3 lines of code (one extra condition) and it will solve this problem.

As always , To solve this problem there is a pre-requisite.
You must first solve/try this problem👇🏼
https://leetcode.com/problems/remove-duplicates-from-sorted-array/description/

Now, Assuming that you have solved or at least read the problem description, the question basically asks to group the unique elements in the starting part of the array (in-place) and return the count of unique elements.

Logic is a simple Two-pointer Approach

**Step 1:** we keep a pointer named $$lastUnique$$ pointing to the last unique element that we processed and another pointer $$current$$ pointing to the current element we are standing at.$$lastUnique$$ will start from 0 as first element is always unique.

**Step2:** At each $$current$$, check two conditions
- If $$current$$ element is equal to the lastUnique element then we can ignore the $$current$$ element.

- Otherwise, swap the $$current$$ element with $$lastUnique + 1$$ index and move $$lastUnique$$ one step ahead. (Now this is my lastUnique element processed)

**Step 3:** In the End , return $$lastUnique + 1$$ as we need to return count and $$lastUnique$$ signifies the index.

Code(Linked Question):
```
public static int removeDuplicates(int[] nums) {
    int n = nums.length;
    if(n == 1) return n;

    int lastUnique = 0;
    for (int current = 1; current < n; current++) {
        if (nums[current] == nums[lastUnique]) {
            continue;
        }else{
            nums[lastUnique + 1] = nums[current];
            lastUnique++;
        }
    }
    return lastUnique  + 1;

    }
```


Now, Coming back to this problem, if you see carefully this question also asks us to group unique elements in the starting part of array **(problem statement of Linked Question)** but know one extra condition is added that the unique element can appear at most twice.

So , now we simply can't ignore the $$current$$ element if it is equal to $$lastUnique$$, **we need to check if there exists an element to the left of $$lastUnique$$ that is equal to $$current$$ element, if it is then ignore the $$current$$ element (as duplicate already considered) otherwise we need to add the $$current$$ element to $$lastUnique$$. (Read the bold part again to get better clarity)**

You are done. Just copy the code and in place of $$continue$$ add the extra condition check and submit it to beat 💯%.
Congratulations, you have developed a 0ms solution to a complex(not now😉) problem.

I know this solution can be compressed to 5-6 lines of code but 
**Are those solutions really intuitive..?🤔** **Can you come up with those solutions directly in an interview..?🤔**  Not for an average Coder like me.

