Since now two duplicates are allowed, I introduce a boolean flag to indicate duplicates occurring.

**Remove Duplicates From Sorted Array II**
https://leetcode.com/problems/remove-duplicates-from-sorted-array-ii/
```
class Solution {
    public int removeDuplicates(int[] nums) {
        int res = 0;
        boolean found = false;
        for (int i = 1; i < nums.length; i++) {
            if (found && nums[i-1] == nums[i]) continue; // if duplicate past twice move on
            if (nums[i-1] == nums[i]) found = true; // 1. if first duplicate, record boolean flag
            else found = false; // 2. if not duplicate, reset boolean flag
            nums[++res] = nums[i]; // overwrite for both cases
        }
        return ++res;
    }
}
```
To see why both 1 and 2 cases should overwrite, consider the example `[0,0,1,1,1,1,2,3,3]`.
For case 2, it is clear that the array index at res should be overwritten: a new unduplicated number has been introduced.
For case 1, without the array index at res overwritten the solution would return `[0,0,1,1,2,3,2,_,_]` not `[0,0,1,1,2,3,3,_,_]`.
To see why, note that at index `i == 8` index `res == 5`. We see a smaller number 2 after the 3 that overwrote index `res`.


This is indicative of a corner case in which the duplicate of the last overwriting number was not reflected properly.
To reflect this corner case the solution faithfully overwrites value at `res` whenever it finds a new duplicate. In the best case, it just redundantly overwrites the duplicate that occurred right before. In the worst case, it properly overwrites the value right next to the duplicate that occurred somewhere much before.

