# Method 3 : Method 2 + Garbage Collector (XD)

## Intuition
So, it's obvious when you grind 15 minutes (check difference between time stamps of previous 2 solutions), you won't expect your code's space complexity to just beat 47.15% of the other JAVA solutions. Hence, this is the intuition to do something crazy!

## Approach
The approach was nothing, but see the best solution that beats 100% space, so I found a solution (by clicking the first bar in the distribution chart).

And you know what? I got to know an amazing technique to tease the LeetCode Judge, by manually running the Garbage Collector of JAVA before returning the answer to each test case.

And the answer is `System.gc();`.

# Complexity
- **Space complexity:**
Space complexity of this new code as expected, did beat all JAVA solutions, (because you literally cleanup everything before returning lol).

- **Time complexity:**
Now, the time complexity (`O(t*c),` where t is number of tc and c is the time to run the garbage collector in 1 call) was definitely a concern, because running so many test cases, everytime manually clearing up memory, would take more worth of time than it took to cleanup some small space in memory. This solution took less time than method 1, but no signs of beating 100% solutions.


## Code
```
class Solution {
    public int removeDuplicates(int[] nums) {
        int cnt = 0, i = 0, j = 0, p = 0;
        while(j<nums.length){
            if(nums[i]==nums[j]){
                if(cnt<2){
                    nums[p++]=nums[j];
                    cnt++;
                }
            }
            else{
                nums[p++]=nums[j];
                i=j;
                cnt=1;
            }
            j++;
        }
        System.gc();
        return p;
    }
}
```


