solutions.content:
**Algorithm**
* If length of nums is less than 2 then simply return length of array
* We can solve this question using two pointers i.e., i and count. Count will track the index of array to be sent and i will track the index of next bigger element
* If current element is less than next element that means only one element is present, then add the ith element in array at count index, incrementing count for next element.
* Else, that means there are more than one elements of that current element. We know that we can add at most two elements, so we will add ith element in the array upto next 2 count pointers. 
* We need to shift the ith element to the next greater element.
* There might be chances that the last element of nums can be remained uncheckd, so once the ith pointer is at second last element then we can add the i+1th element at count place in array.

Time Complexity: O(n) with O(1) extra memory
**Code in Java**
```
class Solution {
    public int removeDuplicates(int[] nums) {
        if(nums.length <= 1) return nums.length;
        int count = 0; 
        for(int i=0; i<nums.length-1; i++){
            if(nums[i] < nums[i+1]) {
                nums[count++] = nums[i];
            }
            else{
                nums[count++] = nums[count++] = nums[i];
                while(i<nums.length-1 && nums[i] >= nums[i+1]) i++;
            }
            if(i+1 == nums.length-1) nums[count++] = nums[i+1];
        }
        return count++;
    }
}
```
