# Intuition
The given code aims to remove duplicates from an array nums and return the new length of the array.

# Approach
1) Create a new array n1 with the same length as nums. This array will store the non-duplicate elements.
2) Initialize variables c, c1, and n to keep track of counts and the length of the new array.
3) Iterate over the elements of nums using the outer for loop.
4) Reset c to zero at the beginning of each outer loop iteration. c will count the number of occurrences of the current element.
5) Use the inner for loop to iterate over nums and check for occurrences of the current element. Increment c for each occurrence.
6) If c is greater than 1, it means the current element is a duplicate.
7) Add the current element twice to n1 (to remove duplicates).
Update c1 and n accordingly.
8) If c is 1, it means the current element is not a duplicate.
Add the current element once to n1.
Update c1 and n accordingly.
9) After the loop ends, copy the elements from n1 back to nums.
Return the final count n, representing the new length of the array after removing duplicates.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(n^2)

- Space complexity:
O(n)

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int removeDuplicates(int[] nums) {
        int [] n1 = new int[nums.length];
        int c=0; 
        int c1=0;      
        int n=0;

        for(int i=0;i<nums.length;i+=c){
             c=0;    
            for(int j=0;j<nums.length;j++){
                if(nums[i]==nums[j]){
                    c+=1;
                }                 
            }
            if(c>1){
                n1[c1]=nums[i];
                c1++;
                n1[c1]=nums[i];
                if(i!=nums.length-1){
                c1++;
                }
                n+=2;               
            }
            else{
                n1[c1]=nums[i];
                 if(i!=nums.length-1){
                c1++;
                }
                n++;
            }          
        }   

        for(int i=0;i<nums.length;i++){
            nums[i]=n1[i];
        }
        return n;
    }
}
```

