The built-in `HashSet` set class already has everything we need, except getting an element by index, so let's use LINQ's `ElementAt` method for that, even though it's a bit slow:
```csharp
public class RandomizedSet
{
    HashSet<int> set = new();
    Random rnd = new();

    public bool Insert(int n) => set.Add(n);

    public bool Remove(int n) => set.Remove(n);

    public int GetRandom() => set.ElementAt(rnd.Next(set.Count));
}
```
To make `GetRandom()` faster, we can convert the set to a list with `ToList()` and only then get an element by index:
```csharp
set.ToList()[rnd.Next(set.Count)];
```

