# Intuition
> Always insert elements in the end of the array and put the index and value in the hashmap

> To Delete, always swap the element with the last element of the array and update the index of the last element in the hashmap and delete the last element from the array and hashmap

> To get random element, return random element from the array from the range: 0 to top-1

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(1)$$ for EachOperation
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(2*10e5)$$, but for Asymptomatic cases, it is $$O(1)$$ since the program do not allocate extra space for the array for the following runtimes.
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class RandomizedSet {
    static int[] arr;
    int top=-1;
    HashMap<Integer,Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
    public RandomizedSet() {
        if(arr==null) arr = new int[200001];
    }

    public boolean insert(int val) {
        if(!map.containsKey(val)){
            top++;
            arr[top]=val;
            map.put(val,top);
            return true;
        }else return false;
    }

    public boolean remove(int val) {
        if(map.containsKey(val)){
            int pos = map.get(val);
            map.put(arr[top],pos);
            arr[pos] = arr[pos] + arr[top] - (arr[top] = arr[pos]); // swapping
            top--;
            map.remove(val);
            return true;
        }else return false;
    }

    public int getRandom() {
        return arr[(int)(Math.random()*(top+1))];
    }
}
```

