solutions.content:
There are 2 classic data structures: list, map
- For O(1) insertion, list and map satisfy
- For O(1) removal by value, map satisfies
- For O(1) getRandom, list satisfies

In order to achive the above at the same time, we maintain both map and list:
- list of values `valList`
- map value to location `valToLoc`

As for removal, the entry should be removed from both `valList` and `valToLoc`.

But removal in `valList` takes O(n) time since it requires all the succeeding elements to be shifted to fill out the space created by removed element.

We can avoid that by swapping `val` with the last element of the list (`if val is not the last one`), and then deleting the last element.

```
    // Map value to location in list.
    private static Map<Integer, Integer> valToLoc;
    // List of values.
    private static List<Integer> valList;
    private static final Random random = new Random();

    /** Initialize your data structure here. */
    public RandomizedSet() {
        valToLoc = new HashMap<>();
        valList = new ArrayList<>();
    }

    /** Inserts a value to the set. Returns true if the set did not already contain the specified element. */
    public boolean insert(int val) {
        if (valToLoc.containsKey(val)) 
            return false;

        valToLoc.put(val, valList.size());
        valList.add(val);

        return true;
    }

    /** Removes a value from the set. Returns true if the set contained the specified element. */
    public boolean remove(int val) {
        if (!valToLoc.containsKey(val))
            return false;

        int posToDelete = valToLoc.get(val);
        valToLoc.remove(val);
        if (posToDelete != valList.size() - 1) {
            int lastVal = valList.get(valList.size() - 1);
            valList.set(posToDelete, lastVal);
            valToLoc.put(lastVal, posToDelete);
        }
        valList.remove(valList.size() - 1);

        return true;
    }

    /** Get a random element from the set. */
    public int getRandom() {
        return valList.get(random.nextInt(valList.size()));
    }
