class RandomizedSet {
public:
    unordered_map<int,int>mp;
    vector<int>arr;

    // Initializes the RandomizedSet object.
    RandomizedSet() { }

	// Inserts an item val into the set if not present.
	//Returns true if the set did not already contain the specified element,
	//false otherwise.
	//count function returns true if val is present in map
    bool insert(int val) {
        if(mp.count(val)){
            return false;
        }
        arr.push_back(val);
        mp[val]=arr.size()-1;
        return true;
    }

	//Removes an item val from the set if present. 
	//Returns true if the set contained the specified element.
    bool remove(int val) {

        if(mp.count(val)){
            int indexx = mp[val];
            int v=arr.back();
            arr[indexx]=v;
            mp[v]=indexx;
            arr.pop_back();
            mp.erase(val);

            return true;
        }
        return false;
    }

	// Get a random element from the set.
	//rand()%arr.size() will give the random element in the 
	//range of arr size.
    int getRandom() {
        int index = rand()%arr.size();
        return arr[index];
    }
};
```

**More Explanation**(found this in discussion section)

Usually the first thing that comes to find when we hear "insert" in constant time is "hashmaps".
That's the reason we use an unordered_map here which stores the element as " key " and its position in vector as the "value ".. The average time complexity of search , insert and remove elements from a hashmap is O(1).

However , here we need to support "Random()" access in O(1) as well. so we are using a vector here to achieve that.
Here is the trick to remove in constant time.
Here is the pseudo-code

1) If the element you are trying to remove is the last element in the vector, remove it, done, ELSE,
2) Read the last element of the vector and write it over the element-to-be-removed

3) Now remove the last element of the vector. (C++ pop_back() in a vector is O(1))
That is exactly the trick we are using here, only that we need to update our hashmap as well.

