First off, you only need a HashSet to solve this in C#

Can your approach work? yes, but it would put your performance, in speed and memory, at the bottom, and you would run into risks

HashSets, by virtue of what they are, inherently handle duplicates, and have O[1] lookups when validating if something exists, so instead of having to add items to a list and a dictionary (which uses a structure similar to a hashset under the hood), your insert becomes this:

    public bool Insert(int val) {
        if (myHashSet.Contains(val))
            return false;
        myHashSet.Add(val);
        return true;
    }

Removal is similar. 
    public bool Remove(int val) {
        if (!set.Contains(val))
            return false;
        set.Remove(val);
        return true;
    }

In Addition to this, you run into an indexing risk. Say your insert order is like this
1,10,4
Your dictionary would be
{{1,0}, {10,1},{4,2}}
If you call remove(10), you would need to
 - Find the index for 10
 - Remove 10 from the list,
 - Remove {10,1} from the dictionary
 - Update every record in your dictionary pointing to index > 1
If you miss this last step (which makes it O(n)), when you then call Remove(4), it will try to look for IX 2, which doesnt exist in your list anymore, throwing an exception. Each of the others carry other issues of varying weight, but all can create unnecessary bugs in your code.

By using a hashset, I was able to get performance in the >90% for speed and >80% for memory.

