I noticed that the fenwick tree approaches (which I believe is more intuitive to me than messing with iterators as I have used BIT for many things related to this) often had a extra logN/logK factor due to binary searching for the value at which the sum function returns >= k / 2 (This is because each sum call on a BIT is O(logN); however, this can be optimized by doing a clever technique on the BIT to find the value in O(log N) (actually, my current implementation has the order function running 30 times always, but this can be optimized as I only initialized it to that to ensure that my jumps are large enough).

More information on this technique can be seen here: https://codeforces.com/blog/entry/61364 as I don't believe I can do a better job explaining. Let me know if there are any questions regarding my code as I think there are some useful things to know (such as index compression + finding an ordered statistic utilizing a fenwick tree). Also let me know if there is anything I should change about my code writing style to make it more understandable.

The basic idea behind this solution is that if an element is present in the current window we're looking at, then it would have a value of >= 1 in an array, whose prefix sum we update using a BIT (we update the position with a 1 to indicate that we're adding it and with a -1 to indicate removal).
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> bit;
    void update(int i, int v) {
        while(i < bit.size()) { // classic BIT update function
            bit[i] += v;
            i += i & -i;
        }
    }
    int order(int k) { // this function computes the position at which the prefix sum of the array is >= k (essentially lower_bound)
        int sum = 0;
        int pos = 0;
        for(int i = 30; i >= 0; i--) {
            if(pos + (1 << i) < bit.size() && sum + bit[pos + (1 << i)] < k) {
                pos += 1 << i;
                sum += bit[pos];
            }
        }
        return pos + 1;
    }
    vector<double> medianSlidingWindow(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        vector<double> ans;
        bit.resize(nums.size() + 10);
        int n = nums.size();
        unordered_map<int,int> m; // this holds the compression from array element -> a smaller index
        vector<int> rev; // holds the reverse operation, from compressed index -> actual value
        vector<int> temp(nums);
        sort(temp.begin(), temp.end()); // essentially, smaller values have smaller indices when compressed
        rev.push_back(0); // we're starting with 1 as the base index as fenwick trees utilize 1 based indexing
        int cnt = 1; // starting value of index compression
        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if(!m.count(temp[i])) {
                m[temp[i]] = cnt++;
                rev.push_back(temp[i]);
            }
        }

        for(int i = 0; i < k; i++) { // initializing the first K elements into the "window"
            update(m[nums[i]], 1);
        }

        for(int i = 0; i < n - k + 1; i++) {
            double median = 0;
            if(k % 2 == 1) {
                median = rev[order(k / 2 + 1)]; // we just look for the position in the BIT with a sum >= k / 2 + 1 (because this is the middle)
            } else {
                int pos1 = order(k / 2); // we take the middle two values
                int pos2 = order(k / 2 + 1);
                median = (long long)rev[pos1] + rev[pos2];
                median /= 2;
            }
            ans.push_back(median);
            if(i < n - k) { // this means as we can move on, we should delete the left end of the window and add the next one
                update(m[nums[i]], -1);
                update(m[nums[i + k]], 1);
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

