# Intuition
My semester exam are coming and i am doing this uff!!
i will ask one question for each rabbit in the forest of some color that how many other rabbits of same color exist 

# Approach
1. Take a hash table to count the frequency of each element in the array
2. After that if map's key==0 that means its unique color rabbit directly add them by map's value in ans
3. If map's key <= maps's value directly add map's value +1 in ans
4. If map's key > map's value then divide them make group and add to answer and if remainder exist on dividing then add map's key +1 in answer.


# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(n) as i am traversing my map and answer vector once.

- Space complexity:
O(n) as i am taking a unordered map for storing the frequency of each elemennt in the answer vector.


# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int numRabbits(vector<int>& answers) {


        unordered_map<int,int> mp; // to count the frequency of each element in array answers
        for(int i=0;i<answers.size();i++)
        {
            mp[answers[i]]++;
        }
        int ans=0;
        for(auto x: mp)
        {
            // if answer[i]==0 then this means there exist a rabbit with unique colour so add all rabbits that has unique colour
            if(x.first==0)    ans+=x.second;
            else
            {
               if(x.second>x.first)
               {
                   // if there is answer[i]=2 that means there are 3 rabbits with the same colour thats why i am doing (x.first+1) to make same rabbits at a group which are talking about each other
                   int m=x.first+1;
                   int quo=x.second  /  m;
                   int mul=quo  *  m;
                  int rem=x.second  %   m;
                   ans+=mul;
                   if(rem)     ans+=m;  
               }
               // else if we cant group them then simply x.first+1 will be added
               else                   ans+=(x.first+1);
            }
        }


     return ans;
    }
};
```

