# Description
My approach requires spatial imagination. Please keep in mind that i'm also not an expert in coding. (I hit 80ms Runtime and 39.7MB of Memory with my code)

# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Evaluate the sides of each column, considering the bordering towers. We also need to add the top and bottom surface if necessary.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
I decided that foreach tower i add the surface of the neigbouring rigth and bottom tower. for the towers that dont have two neigbouring towers just the bottom or rigth surface is calculated. the tower on the bottom rigth thus dont "have" a surface to be determined. Then we need to add the surface areas on the outer side of the complete grid. Also the top and bottom surface has to be added when the heigth of the tower is not 0.


# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(n)

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(1)

# Code
```
public class Solution {
    public int SurfaceArea(int[][] grid)
    {
        int area = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < grid.Length; i++)
        {
            for (int j = 0; j < grid[i].Length; j++)
            {
                //adding top and bottom surface
                if (grid[i][j] != 0)
                    area += 2;  

                //calculating the surface with the neighbouring towers, if existing
                if (i != grid.Length - 1 && j != grid[i].Length - 1)
                {
                    area += Math.Abs(grid[i][j] - grid[i + 1][j]);
                    area += Math.Abs(grid[i][j] - grid[i][j + 1]);
                }
                else if(!(i == grid.Length - 1 && j == grid[i].Length - 1))
                {
                    if (i == grid.Length - 1)
                        area += Math.Abs(grid[i][j] - grid[i][j + 1]);
                    else
