<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
When I saw this question, I thought 2 diffrent solutions. One is with calculating directly. Second is calculating the whole area and subtracting the adjacent areas.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
My approach is the second solution. First I declared two Integer values: totalSurfaceArea, len. It is crystal clear that what they used for. After, I initialized two for loops to loop through the whole grid and check for cubes in each cell.

In first If block, I checked if there is any cubes in cell. If there is, I added the are of cubes like they are a single tower. (For example, 1 cube have 6 units of surface area, 2 cube 10, 3 cube 14. As you can see they have a stable increment. So the formula is area = 6 * cubeCount - 2 * cubeCount) I used the formula for calculating units in a tower. After that, I subtract the hidden areas horizontally. The idea behind the method I use to subtract is: I sent two adjacent block to Math.min() method (Math.min() method compares two arguments and finds the lowest.) And subtract from two sides by multiplying two. (I select the lower tower and subtract Its surfaces two times.) I also did the same on the other. Just vertically.
